(112, 1, '2011-02-03 19:55:55', '2011-02-03 19:55:55', '          After my first break in Spain, a period of time I spend resting, meeting up with my friends and my family, I went back to Dublin, full of energy and looking forward to meeting my class mates again. However, as I told you in the last post, a few of them had already left finished their <a title="English Classes Dublin / Ireland" href="http://www.ulearn.ie/quality_english_courses_dublin" target="_blank">English classes in Dublin</a>, so my group was a little bit <a href="http://dev.wp/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/visita-angc3a9lica-019.jpg"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-87" title="Visita Angélica 019" src="http://dev.wp/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/visita-angc3a9lica-019.jpg?w=300" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a>different. That’s why my school, knowing about this problem, usually holds parties some Friday nights, or even arranges visits to museums, theatres and so on. It’s very useful to have a wide idea of the city and to know about the places it offers you.\n\n            Even though I know it’s quite difficult to give an overview of a city in only one post, I’d like to try it, so overall this is what you can find while visiting Dublin:\n\n            --&gt;Apart from the famous pub area that almost everybody knows, called Temple Bar, on the north side of the city you can also visit the Botanic Gardens, which thanks to the rainy Irish weather, remains green throughout the year. Close to the Botanic Gardens you can even visit the Cementery! I know, maybe you think I’m teasing you but there you can find the tomb of Daniel O’Connel and the tombs of other important men in Irish history. In addition, the cemetery is also quite beautiful.\n\n            --&gt;The city center is where you can see Dublin’s newest landmark, The Spire, and on the other side of the River Liffey, as I told before, there is Temple Bar. I advise you it’s a dangerous area, you always go back home very very drunk jajaja.\n\n            --&gt;On the south side there are several monuments and beautiful streets, like Molly Malone, Grafton Street, Oscar Wilde’s house or St Stephen''s Green Park, where my <a title="English Language school" href="http://www.ulearn.ie/english_courses_ulearn" target="_blank">English language school</a> is located.\n\n            --&gt;And fi<a href="http://dev.wp/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/de-reyes-a-visita-vero-0521.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-88" title="De Reyes a visita Vero 052" src="http://dev.wp/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/de-reyes-a-visita-vero-0521.jpg?w=300" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a>nally, inside of the city, on the west side, you absolutely have to visit the old prison, Kilmainham Gaol, where several important leaders of the Irish independence were hung and even some films were filmed, like In the Name of the Father. Near the prison you also should visit The Guinness Storehouse, where you can sample a very cold Guinness in the restaurant on the top floor!!\n\n            I’ll upload some photos so you’ll able to have an idea what i’m talking about.\n\n            So guys, enjoy the rest of the week!!', 'KNOWING ABOUT DUBLIN (From my English language school)', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', '85-revision', '', '', '2011-02-03 19:55:55', '2011-02-03 19:55:55', '', 85, 'http://dev.wp/?p=112', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
