(219, 1, '2011-04-15 12:00:05', '2011-04-15 12:00:05', 'When the <a href="http://www.ulearn.ie/quality_english_courses_dublin" target="_blank">English Class</a> was finished, one day of last week, I and some friends of the <a href="http://www.ulearn.ie/english_school_dublin" target="_blank">English School Dublin</a> decided to go for an <a href="http://www.thebuenavista.com/irishcoffee.html" target="_blank">Irish coffee</a> on a pub near my house.  We hadn’t tried it before, and I think you should try it if you are living in Ireland.\r\n\r\nIn the pub, there were 3 men playing <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Folk_music_of_Ireland" target="_blank">folk music</a> and the atmosphere was very nice. In this moment someone asked a question: Who invented this delicious drink?\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">\nAccording to the legend, the Irish coffee was invented by Joseph Sheridan, a head chef in Foynes. A group of American passengers had arrived in a flying boat on a miserable winter night in the 1940s. Was in this moment, when Sherindan added whiskey and cram to the coffee to warm the passengers. One of them asked to him if it was Brazilian coffee, and Serindan replayed: no, it’s Irish coffee.</p>\r\nThen, a travel writer of San Francisco tried this coffee in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_Airport" target="_blank">Shannon Airport</a>, and it was started to serve in San Francisco in 1952.', 'Irish coffee', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'irish-coffee', '', '', '2013-04-11 22:43:06', '2013-04-11 22:43:06', '', 0, 'http://dev.wp/?p=219', 0, 'post', '', 0),
