(288, 1, '2011-05-07 19:02:03', '2011-05-07 19:02:03', '[caption id="" align="alignleft" width="213"]<img class=" " alt="" src="http://www.tsc.com.ar/actual/fotos/hurlin.jpg" width="213" height="300" /> Hurling[/caption]\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">On my first’s days in Ireland and when I started my <a href="http://ulearn.ie/quality_english_courses_dublin" target="_blank">English classes Dublin</a>, some months ago, some people of my <a href="http://ulearn.ie/quality_english_courses_dublin" target="_blank">English classes Dublin</a> told me that there are two <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sport_in_Ireland" target="_blank">Irish sports</a>: Hurling and Gaelic football. And I though it’s something more to know about Ireland.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Both sports are played in teams of 15 players, and they have the same objective: to score throwing the ball into the opponent’s goalpost. The goalpost is similar as the football one, with two vertical posts that resemble a rugby goal. The score between these two bars is 3 points, and one point under them.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><img class="alignright" alt="" src="http://www.canadianalodging.com/uploads/hurling2.jpg" width="180" height="119" /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Hurling is played with wooden sticks called <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurley_(stick)" target="_blank">hurley</a> or Camán and a small ball called sliotar. You can hit or carry the ball with the hurley, but is also allowed to allowed to throw it with your hand.\r\nMoreover, Gaelic football is played with a ball with the same size as the football one and can be passed in any directions.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The duration of both matches is 70 minutes, and both are played outdoors.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">In 1884 was founded the <a href="http://www.gaa.ie/" target="_blank">Gaelic Athletic Association </a>(GAA), for the preservation and practice of these sports.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">I haven’t had the chance to watch a match, but I would like to watch one. And it’s normal to see children with hurleys on the streets.</p>', 'HURLING AND GAELIC FOOTBALL', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'hurling-and-gaelic-football', '', '', '2013-04-12 05:22:32', '2013-04-12 04:22:32', '', 0, 'http://dev.wp/?p=288', 0, 'post', '', 0),
