(344, 3, '2011-04-01 13:23:07', '2011-04-01 13:23:07', '<img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-151" title="Map" src="http://dev.wp/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/P2200368-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="180" height="135" />We don''t have clases on the <a title="English School Dublin" href="http://www.ulearn.ie/english_school_dubln" target="_blank">english school Dublin</a> on weekends, so we tend to visit others cities or towns.\r\nA good option was <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howth" target="_blank">Howth</a>, a little fishing village on a hill surrounded by cliffs. It’s at 15 kilometres from the centre of Dublin.\r\n\r\nSo, we left the Conolly Station at 10.45am, and we spent 20 minutes to arrive to Howth. Out of the station, we saw a map where were 4 indicated routes. We decided to make the long one, which goes around the whole peninsula.\r\n\r\nJust when we started to walk, we saw the Ireland’s Eye, an islet near Howth. Unfortunately the weather wasn’t very good so, we couldn’t see it very well. We noticed that in summer there are some boats for arrive there and visit the monastery’s runes.\r\n\r\n<img class="size-medium wp-image-152 alignleft" src="http://dev.wp/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/P2200332-225x300.jpg" alt="" width="203" height="270" />\r\n\r\nWe walked along the cliffs, through a narrow and muddy path (It’d rained the night before). We came across a little beach and we saw the lighthouse. We were walking during 2 hours so we decided to stop and to eat some food we’d taken from home. After this short break, we continued with our route. We were surprised when we had to cross the <a href="http://www.howthgolfclub.ie/">golf course</a>, following some white stones indicating the path.\r\n\r\nThe route finishes in the same place where it starts, so we arrived at the station, and in front of it, there was a little <a href="http://www.irishfarmersmarkets.ie/howth.html" target="_blank">market.</a> Then, we went to the port, where we could see some seals waiting for some fish that people were giving them.\r\n\r\nWe were so tired, and we had cold so we entered to a bar with views on the port to get a tea. Then we returned to Dublin. We arrived there at 7pm and, like every Sunday, we went to get a beer in a Pub in Dame Street to close the week with a good concert and start again another week of <a title="English Classes Dublin / Ireland" href="http://www.ulearn.ie/quality_english_courses_dublin" target="_blank">English classes Dublin</a>', 'VISITING HOWTH', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '150-revision-7', '', '', '2011-04-01 13:23:07', '2011-04-01 13:23:07', '', 150, 'http://dev.wp/150-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(345, 3, '2011-03-31 16:15:43', '2011-03-31 16:15:43', 'Buenas!\r\n\r\nSoy y a partir de ahora voy a ser yo quien escriba el blog por un tiempo.\r\n\r\nLlevo viviendo en Dublín desde enero, y aunque a veces el tiempo fastidie un poco, Irlanda es un país precioso.\r\n\r\nComo no sé cómo empezar, creo que estaría bien hablaros un poco sobre los Pubs i Clubes de Dublín, que es un tema que tuvimos que exponer en la escuela de Ingles en Dublin.\r\n\r\nLos Pubs son muy comunes en Irlanda, i toman un rol importante en la vida social irlandesa. Esta palabra proviene de las “Public Houses”, donde se encontraban los trabajadores y viajeros para tomar algo y relajarse después de su jornada.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-145" title="guilligans_pxl_d0de428f640c81a86ff6e1da920817b8" src="http://dev.wp/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/guilligans_pxl_d0de428f640c81a86ff6e1da920817b8-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" />\r\n\r\nHay pubs de muchos tipos, y en Dublín, la zona de Pubs i Clubes más popular es el <a href="http://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temple_Bar" target="_blank">Temple Bar</a>. En consecuencia, esta zona es la más turística, especialmente los fines de semana. Así que si algún día os dais una vuelta por allí, lo más posible es que oigáis todo tipo de idiomas, especialmente, aparte del inglés,  el castellano y el portugués. Allí puedes disfrutar de música en directo y música tradicional. Aunque yo recomiendo alejarse del centro y buscar un pub donde solo enco\r\n\r\nntréis irlandeses. Yo he podido comprobar que son muy bromistas y en general son simpáticos y hospitalarios y dispuestos a hablar de todo tipo de temas.\r\n\r\nEs típico en Irlanda hacer rondas en los pubs, así que es casi imposible tomar sólo una cerveza.\r\n\r\nLos pubs cierran a las 23:30 de domingo a jueves, y los viernes y sábados cierran a las 00:30, pero en los pubs del centro cierran más tarde, entre 1:30 y 2:30, con un margen de media hora para acabarte la última copa.\r\n\r\nPor otro lado, los clubes abren entre 11 y 12 de la noche y cierran a las 3.\r\n\r\nCon la gente de la escuela de inglés, los martes solemos ir a un club llamado Diceys, a mí personalmente no me gusta, pero es una buena oportunidad para conocer gente de la escuela, y aparte, hacen precios especiales, así que también es una manera de no gastar tanto al salir.', 'Pubs y Clubes', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '144-revision-4', '', '', '2011-03-31 16:15:43', '2011-03-31 16:15:43', '', 144, 'http://dev.wp/144-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(346, 3, '2011-03-31 16:16:14', '2011-03-31 16:16:14', '<p style="text-align: left;">Hi,</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">I''m , and I''m going to write this blog from now.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">I’ve been living in Dublin since middle-June, sometimes the weather is not really good, but Ireland is a very beautiful country.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">I’m going to start talking about Pubs and Clubs, because we had to present this issue orally in the <a title="English Language school" href="http://www.ulearn.ie/english_courses_ulearn" target="_blank">English language school</a> in Dublin last week.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Pubs are very common in Ireland. They play an important role in the Irish social life. The word “Pub” comes from the “Public Houses”, where travelers and workers used to meet to get a drink and relax after t</p>\r\n<img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-140" title="Pub" src="http://dev.wp/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/75imagen-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" />\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">heir day.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">There are pubs of lots of types. Maybe <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temple_Bar,_Dublin" target="_blank">Temple Bar</a> is the most popular area in Dublin and, in consequence, it’s very touristic, especially on weekends. So, if some day you go around there, you’ll heard lots of languages, especially, a part of English, Spanish and Portuguese.  But I recommend moving away from the city centre and looking for a pub with only Irish people.</p>\r\nIt’s common for Irish people to do rounds, so, if you do that, it’s almost impossible to drink only a beer.\r\n\r\nPubs tend to close at 11.30pm from Sunday to Thursday, and at 12.30am Fridays and Saturdays. In town it’s more common for them to close between 1.30 and 2.30am.\r\n\r\nMoreover, clubs tend to open later than pubs, between 11pm and 12am, and they close at 3am.\r\n\r\nIt’s normal for people of my English School to go out on Tuesdays, to a club called Diceys, I don’t really like it, but it’s a good way to meet people from the school. There are also special prices this day, so it’s a good way for not spend so much too.', 'Pubs and Clubs', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '139-revision-5', '', '', '2011-03-31 16:16:14', '2011-03-31 16:16:14', '', 139, 'http://dev.wp/139-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
